<h1>Master’s Research Proposal</h1>
<h1>Physics-Guided Efficient Detection of AI-Generated Face Images Based on Camera Imaging Noise</h1>
<p style="text-align:center">Research Field: Image Processing / Digital Image Forensics / AI-Generated Face Detection</p>
<h2>1. Research Topic</h2>
<p>This proposal focuses on efficient and accurate discrimination between AI-generated face images and real face images. The central idea is to move beyond model-specific visual artifacts and build a detection framework grounded in the physical imaging process of cameras and electronic sensors. The tentative topic is: Physics-Guided Efficient Detection of AI-Generated Face Images Based on Camera Imaging Noise.</p>
<h2>2. Research Background and Significance</h2>
<p>In recent years, GANs, diffusion models, and hybrid generation systems have greatly improved the visual quality of synthetic human faces. Generated faces are no longer limited to obvious artifacts such as distorted eyes, irregular teeth, or unnatural backgrounds. Modern diffusion-based and GAN-refined models can produce highly realistic skin texture, lighting, and facial geometry. As a result, both human perception and conventional RGB classifiers are becoming less reliable.</p>
<p>The key observation behind this research is that realistic appearance does not necessarily imply physical authenticity. A real face image is produced through a continuous physical imaging chain, including light propagation, lens projection, sensor sampling, color filter array interpolation, image signal processing, compression, and sensor noise. By contrast, an AI-generated face is produced through statistical fitting in pixel space or latent space. Even when it appears visually convincing, it does not naturally inherit the same sensor lineage as a camera-captured image.</p>
<p>Therefore, the research problem can be reframed. Instead of asking whether an image looks fake, this project asks whether the image carries the physical traces expected from real imaging devices. This perspective is important for digital media security, online identity verification, social platform governance, and forensic evidence analysis.</p>
<h2>2.1 Theoretical Thinking: The Development Path Toward Undetectable Generation and the Physical Definition of RealityFrom the historical development of image generation, a clear evolutionary path can be observed. GANs first tried to approximate the real image distribution through adversarial learning; StyleGAN further organized face generation in a controllable latent space; diffusion models then reframed generation as a gradual denoising process; recent hybrid systems combine diffusion backbones with GAN-style high-frequency refinement. Along this path, generated images are becoming increasingly close to the dense region of the real-image distribution.This trend raises a meaningful theoretical possibility: a future unified generation system may produce images that are visually indistinguishable to humans and difficult for many statistical detectors to recognize. In such a scenario, detection can no longer rely mainly on visible artifacts, facial abnormality, or the signature of a particular generator. The more generation models learn to imitate the statistical manifold of real images, the more fragile surface-level detection becomes.However, this possibility naturally leads to a deeper distinction between visual realism and physical reality. A generated image may become statistically typical and perceptually convincing, but it is not necessarily the result of physical light entering an optical device and being sampled by a real sensor. Therefore, the concept of &#x27;real&#x27; should have a physical definition in forensic detection: a real image is not merely an image that looks real, but an image that can be explained by a physically plausible camera acquisition process.This theoretical analysis strengthens the motivation of this proposal. If future AI-generated faces become visually indistinguishable, the most stable detection basis may shift from &#x27;finding what is fake&#x27; to &#x27;verifying whether physical imaging evidence exists&#x27;. In other words, the detector should test whether the image contains the noise, demosaicing traces, optical response, and sensor lineage that a real camera image should carry.3. Research Objectives</h2>
<h2>2.1 Theoretical Thinking: The Development Path Toward Undetectable Generation and the Physical Definition of Reality</h2>
<p>From the historical development of image generation, a clear evolutionary path can be observed. GANs first tried to approximate the real image distribution through adversarial learning; StyleGAN further organized face generation in a controllable latent space; diffusion models then reframed generation as a gradual denoising process; recent hybrid systems combine diffusion backbones with GAN-style high-frequency refinement. Along this path, generated images are becoming increasingly close to the dense region of the real-image distribution.</p>
<p>This trend raises a meaningful theoretical possibility: a future unified generation system may produce images that are visually indistinguishable to humans and difficult for many statistical detectors to recognize. In such a scenario, detection can no longer rely mainly on visible artifacts, facial abnormality, or the signature of a particular generator. The more generation models learn to imitate the statistical manifold of real images, the more fragile surface-level detection becomes.</p>
<p>However, this possibility naturally leads to a deeper distinction between visual realism and physical reality. A generated image may become statistically typical and perceptually convincing, but it is not necessarily the result of physical light entering an optical device and being sampled by a real sensor. Therefore, the concept of &#x27;real&#x27; should have a physical definition in forensic detection: a real image is not merely an image that looks real, but an image that can be explained by a physically plausible camera acquisition process.</p>
<p>This theoretical analysis strengthens the motivation of this proposal. If future AI-generated faces become visually indistinguishable, the most stable detection basis may shift from &#x27;finding what is fake&#x27; to &#x27;verifying whether physical imaging evidence exists&#x27;. In other words, the detector should test whether the image contains the noise, demosaicing traces, optical response, and sensor lineage that a real camera image should carry.</p>
<p>• To analyze the differences between AI-generated face images and real face images from the perspective of physical imaging noise, including shot noise, read noise, demosaicing traces, JPEG residuals, and PRNU-like sensor patterns.</p>
<p>• To design an efficient multi-branch detection model that combines RGB semantics, frequency-domain residuals, and camera-noise-oriented features.</p>
<p>• To improve cross-generator generalization, especially under unseen GAN, diffusion, and diffusion-GAN hybrid face generators.</p>
<p>• To reduce model complexity and inference cost so that the proposed method can be used in practical real-time or near-real-time scenarios.</p>
<p>• To provide interpretable evidence by localizing suspicious regions and visualizing frequency/noise residual responses.</p>
<h2>4. Current Research Status</h2>
<p>Early AI face detection methods mainly relied on visible artifacts generated by GANs, such as checkerboard patterns, abnormal facial symmetry, inconsistent backgrounds, and high-frequency texture defects. These methods achieved good accuracy on known generators, but their performance often dropped significantly when tested on unseen models or post-processed images.</p>
<p>With the development of StyleGAN, StyleGAN2, DDPM, latent diffusion models, and recent face-specific generation pipelines, synthetic faces have become more difficult to detect using simple visual cues. Diffusion models in particular tend to remove many low-level GAN artifacts, while GAN-based refiners can restore high-frequency facial details. This weakens traditional artifact-based detection.</p>
<p>Recent research has explored frequency analysis, wavelet transforms, edge inconsistency learning, vision transformers, CLIP-based forensic adapters, and face security foundation models. These methods improve generalization to some extent, but many of them still primarily learn statistical differences in datasets rather than explicitly modeling the physical origin of real images. The gap this proposal addresses is the lack of a lightweight and physically interpretable framework that tests whether an image contains traces consistent with real camera acquisition.</p>
<h2>5. Research Content and Methodology</h2>
<h2>5.1 Physical Imaging Noise Analysis</h2>
<p>The first part of the research will analyze the camera imaging process and identify measurable traces that are difficult for generative models to reproduce. These may include sensor noise distribution, local noise variance under different illumination levels, CFA/demosaicing periodicity, lens-related spatial distortion, chromatic response, and compression residual patterns. Both theoretical analysis and empirical measurement will be used.</p>
<h2>5.2 Dataset Construction and Preprocessing</h2>
<p>A balanced experimental dataset will be constructed from public real-face datasets and AI-generated face datasets. Real images should include different camera sources, illumination conditions, resolutions, and compression qualities. Fake images should cover GAN-based faces, diffusion-based faces, face swapping, inpainting, and text-to-image or image-to-image generated faces. Preprocessing will include face alignment, region-of-interest extraction, residual map generation, frequency transformation, and quality normalization.</p>
<h2>5.3 Multi-Branch Lightweight Detection Network</h2>
<p>The proposed framework will contain three complementary branches. The RGB branch captures semantic facial consistency. The frequency branch extracts wavelet or Fourier-domain high-frequency residuals. The physical-noise branch focuses on sensor-related inconsistency, such as abnormal noise distribution, missing demosaicing traces, and pseudo-random texture regularity. Features from the three branches will be fused using attention or gated fusion, followed by a lightweight classifier.</p>
<h2>5.4 Training Strategy and Loss Design</h2>
<p>The model will be trained with binary classification loss, domain generalization constraints, and contrastive loss between real physical noise traces and generated pseudo-noise traces. To avoid overfitting to a specific generator, leave-one-generator-out evaluation and data augmentation will be used. Compression, resizing, blur, and social-media-style post-processing will be introduced to test robustness.</p>
<h2>5.5 Evaluation and Explainability</h2>
<p>The system will be evaluated using accuracy, AUC, F1-score, equal error rate, cross-generator performance, inference speed, parameter size, and robustness under post-processing. Explainability will be provided through residual heatmaps, frequency response visualization, and region-level evidence analysis.</p>
<h2>6. Innovation Points</h2>
<p>• It introduces development-path analysis as part of the research logic: as generative models move toward visually undetectable images, the study argues that forensic detection must be grounded in the physical definition of reality rather than only in perceptual realism.</p>
<p>• The project shifts the detection criterion from appearance-based artifact recognition to physical camera lineage verification.</p>
<p>• It explicitly integrates physical noise priors, frequency-domain residuals, and lightweight deep learning into a unified detection framework.</p>
<p>• It aims to improve generalization to unseen generators by focusing on traces that real cameras should possess rather than defects that fake images may expose.</p>
<p>• It emphasizes practical efficiency through a compact multi-branch network and region-focused analysis instead of relying only on large vision foundation models.</p>
<p>• It provides interpretable forensic evidence, making the result more useful for real-world image verification and digital forensics.</p>
<h2>7. Feasibility Analysis</h2>
<p>The research is feasible because it is based on established image processing tools such as wavelet transform, Fourier analysis, noise residual extraction, and convolutional neural networks. Public datasets can support initial experiments, while additional real images from different devices can be collected to strengthen the physical-noise analysis. The project does not require training a large generative model from scratch; it mainly requires feature extraction, detector design, controlled experiments, and comparative evaluation.</p>
<h2>8. Research Schedule</h2>
<p><b>Stage</b></p>
<p><b>Time</b></p>
<p><b>Main Tasks</b></p>
<p>1</p>
<p>Months 1-3</p>
<p>Literature review; summarize GAN, diffusion, and AI face forensic detection methods; define the research hypothesis.</p>
<p>2</p>
<p>Months 4-6</p>
<p>Build datasets; design preprocessing pipeline; extract noise residuals and frequency-domain features.</p>
<p>3</p>
<p>Months 7-10</p>
<p>Develop the multi-branch lightweight detection network and conduct baseline experiments.</p>
<p>4</p>
<p>Months 11-14</p>
<p>Improve cross-generator generalization; add robustness tests under compression, blur, resizing, and post-processing.</p>
<p>5</p>
<p>Months 15-18</p>
<p>Conduct ablation studies, efficiency analysis, and explainability visualization.</p>
<p>6</p>
<p>Months 19-24</p>
<p>Complete thesis writing, polish experiments, and prepare possible conference or journal submission.</p>
<h2>9. Expected Outcomes</h2>
<p>• A physics-guided detection framework for distinguishing AI-generated face images from real camera-captured face images.</p>
<p>• A set of reproducible experiments comparing RGB, frequency, residual, and physical-noise-based detection strategies.</p>
<p>• An efficient model suitable for practical deployment scenarios.</p>
<p>• Visualized forensic evidence showing why a sample is judged real or fake.</p>
<p>• A master’s thesis and, if experimental results are strong enough, a publishable research paper.</p>
